25|$|There {{are many}} {{concerns}} regarding the {{environmental effects of}} the manufacture of hydrogen. Hydrogen is made either by electrolysis of water, or by <b>fossil</b> <b>fuel</b> reforming. Reforming a <b>fossil</b> <b>fuel</b> leads to a higher {{emissions of carbon dioxide}} compared with direct use of the <b>fossil</b> <b>fuel</b> in an internal combustion engine. Similarly, if hydrogen is produced by electrolysis from fossil-fuel powered generators, increased carbon dioxide is emitted in comparison with direct use of the <b>fossil</b> <b>fuel.</b>|$|R
